# Should we relocate our family across the country for this job offer?

I got an offer that looks like a big step up, but the more I run the numbers the less obvious it gets. I'd like a clear-eyed read before we uproot the kids. I've laid out both our current life and what year one would actually look like.

## Us
- Married, I'm **39**, my spouse is **37**. Two kids, ages **5 and 8**.
- We **rent** in a comfortable mid-cost metro where we have family nearby and a lot of childcare help.
- I'm the primary earner. My spouse works **part-time ($34,000/year)** and would almost certainly have to quit and job-hunt from scratch in the new city.
- We are stable but not wealthy. We have about **$70,000 in savings** and no debt beyond two car loans (in the budget below).

## The offer
- New role, big-name employer, in a **high-cost coastal metro** clear across the country.
- **Base salary $176,000** (I'm at **$128,000** now — a **+37.5%** raise on my own line) plus a **one-time $20,000 sign-on bonus**.
- Genuinely better career trajectory: bigger team, more scope, a title bump. This is the kind of move that compounds.
- Relocation help is minimal — a flat **$20,000 sign-on** is basically it. We estimate the actual move (movers, deposits, travel, setup) at about **$18,000**, so the bonus roughly covers the move and not much else.

## Current life — the real monthly cash flow
Household **take-home: $9,990/month** (my $128k + spouse's $34k, after tax and benefits).

| Item | Monthly |
|---|---|
| Rent | $2,200 |
| Childcare / aftercare (2 kids) | $1,150 |
| Groceries + household | $1,200 |
| Two cars: payments, gas, insurance | $940 |
| Dining, entertainment, subscriptions | $560 |
| Utilities + phones + internet | $480 |
| Health/dental premiums (post-tax) | $320 |
| Misc / clothing / gifts | $390 |
| **Total expenses** | **$7,240** |

That leaves us saving **$2,750/month** ($9,990 − $7,240) today.

## Year one in the new city — same budget, new prices, one income
My spouse earns **$0** the first year (assume a full year to re-land part-time work). Household **take-home drops to $10,267/month** — yes, slightly *higher* than now, because my raise more than offsets losing the spouse's smaller paycheck, even after the higher tax bracket and high-tax state.

| Item | Monthly |
|---|---|
| Rent (comparable home, high-cost metro) | $4,100 |
| Childcare / aftercare (2 kids) | $1,350 |
| Groceries + household | $1,450 |
| Two cars: payments, gas, insurance | $940 |
| Dining, entertainment, subscriptions | $620 |
| Utilities + phones + internet | $560 |
| Health/dental premiums (post-tax) | $320 |
| Misc / clothing / gifts | $390 |
| **Total expenses** | **$9,730** |

That leaves us saving only **$537/month** ($10,267 − $9,730).

## The tension, in one line
A **+37.5% raise** turns into our monthly savings **falling from $2,750 to $537** in year one — a **~$2,213/month** swing — almost entirely because **rent jumps +$1,900/month** ($2,200 → $4,100) and we lose the spouse's income and our free family childcare. If my spouse lands even a **$42,000** job in year two, household take-home rises roughly **+$2,590/month** and the whole picture flips strongly positive — but that's a bet on them re-employing in a city where we know no one.

## The honest context
The career upside is real and probably the biggest driver of our long-run income. But we'd be trading a supported, cash-positive life near family for a tighter, isolated, more expensive one — at least for a year, maybe longer. The kids are young enough to move easily now and that window won't stay open.

Do we take it? And if we do, what would have to be true (offer terms, timeline, spouse's plan) for this to be the right call rather than a prestige trap?

